@flexiarg vsatlatarium/vapor-as-affect
@title Vapor as Affective Dimension
@audience interaction designers, exhibition designers
@tone analytic
@style design-pattern
@sigils [🌸/气]
@references [vsatlatarium/dome-projection vsatlas/interpretive-views]

! conclusion:
  Use a continuous "vapor" slider to control atmospheric intensity —
  bloom, glow, particles, colour shift — so viewers can modulate the
  affective register of the constellation without changing its structure.

  + context: You are designing an interface where emotional tone is a parameter alongside structural navigation. This does not apply to purely analytic views where atmosphere would be misleading.
  + IF:
    The same constellation serves both analytical review and evocative
    exhibition contexts.

  + HOWEVER:
    A fixed aesthetic either feels too clinical for exhibition or too
    decorative for analysis.

  + THEN:
    Provide a single slider that continuously blends from minimal
    (dark, precise, subtle arcs) to maximal (pink glow, bloom on arcs,
    particle dust, background colour shift, hover halos). The underlying
    data stays identical.

  + BECAUSE:
    Separating affect from structure lets the same tool serve a
    facilitator's workshop (vapor low) and a gallery wall (vapor high)
    without rebuilding the view.

  + STATUS:
    status[ready]
    evidence[VSATLATARIUM vapor slider — dome glow, arc bloom, particle dust, background shift]

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[Test whether high-vapor mode influences which stories viewers explore first (affect-driven navigation).]
    next[Consider per-cluster vapor levels to highlight focal stories in a facilitated session.]
